data.content:
## What breaks: Sync I/O on EF Core Cosmos is fully removed

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider disabled sync I/O by default but allowed a **sync-over-async opt-in**. In **EF Core 11, that opt-in is gone** — all synchronous calls **always throw**, with no workaround.

Every method in your `ProductRepository` is affected:

| Call | Replacement |
|------|-------------|
| `.ToList()` | `await .ToListAsync()` |
| `.First(...)` | `await .FirstAsync(...)` |
| `.Count()` | `await .CountAsync()` |
| `.SaveChanges()` | `await .SaveChangesAsync()` |

Your repository must become async:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

All callers of these methods must also be updated to `await` the results. This is a cascading change — the `async` propagates up the call stack.

**Also note** for your Cosmos DB usage: owned collections with no items now return an **empty collection instead of `null`**, so update any `is null` checks to `.Count == 0`.
